- description: A recurring spreadsheet failure mode is answering in the workbook with explanatory text, VBA, or code-like content when the task is actually evaluated on the saved workbook state and specific result cells. The mixed evidence in task 269-44 shows the decisive difference: successful rollouts inspected the workbook, performed the requested transformation, and saved cell values reflecting the resulting workbook state, while failed rollouts pasted explanatory macro/code text into target cells. The all-fail task 51-12 also showed weaker corroboration of the same output-modality confusion: some rollouts wrote code/formula text instead of the spreadsheet answer. Existing base-skill coverage already says to use openpyxl to read and write xlsx files, and the all-success task 13-1 corroborates that direct workbook editing flow is productive when tasks require in-place workbook mutation and saving.
- latest_executor_action: When a spreadsheet task provides an input workbook, an output workbook path, and evaluator-visible cells, treat the workbook as the primary output artifact. Inspect the actual workbook, execute the requested mutation with openpyxl, and write only the resulting spreadsheet values needed in the checked cells; do not paste explanations, VBA, or code snippets into worksheet cells unless the task explicitly asks for code to be stored there.
- remedy_log:
